If we go back to 2014, automation existed — but it wasn’t scalable.
We had fewer than 1,000 test cases, no pipeline integration, and most testing happened after release. It was largely manual.

In 2016, we made a key decision.
We moved to open-source tools like Selenium. That gave us flexibility, reduced dependency costs, and most importantly — control over our direction. That became our foundation.

Between 2017 and 2019, automation started supporting production releases.
We moved from experimenting to actually relying on automation. Coverage grew, but more importantly, team confidence grew.

The real turning point came in 2020.
We integrated automation into our CI/CD pipelines. Testing shifted from post-release validation to build-driven validation. That changed everything.

From there, growth accelerated.
We expanded into Provider and Encounter file validations, supporting hundreds of files each month and reducing risk in state reporting.

By 2024, automation became part of the standard release process across nearly 60 applications.
Today, we execute over one million automated validations annually.

We grew from under 1,000 validations to over one million — completely changing how we deliver release confidence.

What started as an efficiency initiative has now become an enterprise-scale quality engine.
